    <a title="Liliyana Shadowlyn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/51641311-liliyana-shadowlyn"><img alt="Liliyana Shadowlyn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1627098510p2/51641311.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4277755948?book_show_action=true">Oct 07, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Liliyana Shadowlyn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Liliyana Shadowlyn" href="/user/show/51641311-liliyana-shadowlyn">Liliyana Shadowlyn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/51641311-liliyana-shadowlyn?shelf=2021-reads">2021-reads</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4277755948" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8695269102888790342">I found this to be quite an interesting read. My first thought, as I dove in with the first essay, was that my Literature and Technology professor back in college would have loved this book (it definitely would have fit in with some of what we covered). I thought the essays were well-thought-out and well written, but not too heavy. This would be easy for anyone to jump into, although I recommend reading only one essay at a time. If you’re a fan of philosophy, or where humans are headed as a whol</span>
  <span id="freeText8695269102888790342" style="display:none">I found this to be quite an interesting read. My first thought, as I dove in with the first essay, was that my Literature and Technology professor back in college would have loved this book (it definitely would have fit in with some of what we covered). I thought the essays were well-thought-out and well written, but not too heavy. This would be easy for anyone to jump into, although I recommend reading only one essay at a time. If you’re a fan of philosophy, or where humans are headed as a whole, then you’re going to find plenty to enjoy and ponder over in this collection. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8695269102888790342" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


